The opposition part says it wrote to Baleka Mbete 18 days ago, requesting she table the motion. JOHANNESBURG - The Democratic Alliance (DA) says it's considering taking legal actions following Parliament s failure to schedule their motion of no confidence in President Jacob Zuma.The party says its leader Mmusi Maimane wrote to Parliamentary Speaker Baleka Mbete 18 days ago, requesting she table the motion in the National Assembly.Its adds that parliamentary rules are clear regarding the urgency with which a motion of no confidence in a president should be dealt with.The DA s chief whip John Steenhuisen says: The Democratic Alliance is insistent that this motion of no confidence in the president must go ahead and must be heard. The rules of Parliament also say that it has to be prioritised. It has now been 18 days since we first tabled this motion with the speaker. It s an unacceptably long time and now doesn t appear on paper. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)